{{Shintoism}} {{Italic title|reason=[[:Category:Japanese words and phrases]]}} {{nihongo|'''''Fudoki'''''|風土記|}} are ancient reports on [[provinces of Japan|provincial]] culture, geography, and [[oral tradition]] presented to the reigning [[Emperor of Japan|monarchs of Japan]], also known as local [[gazetteers]]. They contain agricultural, geographical, and historical records as well as [[Japanese mythology|mythology]] and [[Japanese folklore|folklore]].{{Sfn|Sakamoto|2011|pp=16-17}} ''Fudoki'' manuscripts also document local myths, rituals, and [[Waka (poetry)|poems]] that are not mentioned in the ''[[Kojiki]]'' and the ''[[Nihon Shoki]]'' chronicles, which are the most important literature of the ancient national mythology and history. In the course of national unification, the imperial court enacted a series of criminal and administrative codes called ''[[ritsuryō]]'' and surveyed the provinces established by such codes to exert greater control over them.{{Sfn|Sakamoto|2011|pp=4-5}}
== Kofudoki == [[Image:Harima Fudoki.jpg|thumb|250px|A scroll of the oldest extant Fudoki from [[Harima Province]] preserved at [[Tenri Central Library]] in [[Tenri, Nara]]]] In the narrower sense, ''Fudoki'' refer to the oldest records written in the [[Nara period]], later called {{nihongo|'''''Kofudoki'''''|古風土記}} (Old-Fudoki). Compilation of ''Kofudoki'' began in 713 and was completed over a 20-year period.{{Sfn|Sakamoto|2011|pp=16-17}} Following the [[Taika Reform]] in 646 and the [[Code of Taihō]] enacted in 701, there was need to centralize and solidify the power of the imperial court. This included accounting for lands under its control. According to the ''[[Shoku Nihongi]]'', [[Empress Genmei]] issued a decree in 713 ordering each {{nihongo|provincial government|[[:ja:国衙]]|kokuga}} to collect and report the following information:{{Sfn|Sakamoto|2011|pp=16-17}}{{Sfn|Kojima|Naoki|Nishimiya|Kuranaka|2007|pp=310-311}} *Names of [[districts of Japan|districts]] and townships *Natural resources and living things *Land fertility *Etymology of [[Japanese place name#Geographic features|names for geographic features]], such as mountains, plains, and rivers *Myths, legends, and folktales told orally by old people
==Names==
[[Empress Genmei]] ordered in 713 that [[Japanese place names|place names]] in the provinces, districts, and townships should be written in two [[kanji]] characters with positive connotations.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://crd.ndl.go.jp/reference/modules/d3ndlcrdentry/index.php?page=ref_view&id=1000151739 | title= 好字令 (good names) | publisher=National Diet Library | work=Collaborative Reference Database | accessdate=28 August 2015}}</ref>{{Sfn|Sakamoto|2011|pp=16-17}} This occasionally required name changes. For example, {{nihongo|Hayatsuhime|速津媛|}} became {{nihongo|Hayami|速見|}} and {{nihongo|Ishinashi no Oki|無石堡|}} became {{nihongo|Ishii|石井|}}.
==Manuscripts==
At least 48 of the [[Gokishichidō]] provinces contributed to their records but only that of [[Izumo Province|Izumo]] remains nearly complete. Partial records of [[Hizen Province|Hizen]], [[Bungo Province|Bungo]], [[Harima Province|Harima]] and [[Hitachi Province|Hitachi]] remain and a few passages from various volumes remain scattered throughout various books.{{Sfn|Sakamoto|2011|pp=16-17}} Those of Harima and Hizen are designated [[List of National Treasures of Japan (writings: Japanese books)#History books and historical tales|National Treasures]].
Below is a list of extant manuscripts and scattered passages.{{Sfn|Sakamoto|2011|p=19}}<ref>[http://homepage2.nifty.com/toka3aki/geography/fudoki_itsu.html 国土としての始原史～風土記逸文] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130104042845/http://homepage2.nifty.com/toka3aki/geography/fudoki_itsu.html |date=2013-01-04 }}</ref>
