{{Nihongo|'''Kanazawa Bunko'''|金沢文庫}}, formally titled the Kanagawa Prefectural Kanazawa-Bunko Museum, is a museum located in [[Kanazawa-ku, Yokohama|Kanazawa]] [[Wards of Japan|Ward]], [[Yokohama]], [[Japan]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Kanazawa Bunko, A Samurai's Library|url=https://en.japantravel.com/kanagawa/kanazawa-bunko-a-samurai-s-library/32748|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref> It features a collection of traditional Japanese and Chinese art objects, many dating from the [[Kamakura period]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Japan National Tourism Guide|url=https://www.jnto.go.jp/eng/spot/museum/kanazawabunkoart.html|website=Japan: the Official Guide|publisher=Japan National Tourism Organization|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref>
Originally build as a private library, Kanazawa Bunko was one of the two most important centers of learning in medieval Japan, with [[Ashikaga Gakkō]] being the other.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Wiegand|first1=Wayne (ed.)|last2=Davis|first2=Donald (ed.)|title=Encyclopedia of Library History|date=1994|publisher=Routledge|isbn=0824057872|page=320|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wFdsBgAAQBAJ&pg=PT353&lpg=PT353&dq=kanazawa+bunko+library&source=bl&ots=__6IIKdRTC&sig=VAoJ3QcFZo3qkedw8xTCow062so&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjft_SJgdfSAhVC7GMKHWquBKQQ6AEINzAF#v=onepage&q=kanazawa%20bunko%20library&f=false|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref> The library was opened in 1275 by [[Kanezawa Sanetoki|Hōjō Sanetoki]] (1224–76), a grandson of [[Hojo Yoshitoki|Hōjō Yoshitoki]], second regent of the [[Kamakura shogunate]]. The library's collection has not remained intact, although some original documents remain. The existing building, built in 1990, houses the existing collection.
The art collection of the Kanazawa Bunko includes [[Kamakura period|Kamakura]] portraits, [[East Asian calligraphy|calligraphy]], Chinese and Japanese classics, Buddhist sutras, and [[Zen]] writings. It is housed in a building within the [[Shōmyōji temple]]'s precincts, though in a separate building.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Allen (ed.)|first1=Susan|title=History and Cultural Heritage of Chinese Calligraphy|date=2010|publisher=IFLA|isbn=978-3-598-22046-3|page=237|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zb5sJ5NGVvIC&pg=PA237&lpg=PA237&dq=kanazawa+bunko+library&source=bl&ots=59AKwhX-i_&sig=ppBftCgdTF-lr1oT4HLJZCyR8Gw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi3q6Gdh9fSAhWIWSYKHbsAC3sQ6AEIQTAH#v=onepage&q=kanazawa%20bunko%20library&f=false}}</ref> The collection includes an eleven-headed [[Kannon]] (Goddess of Mercy), a [[Maitreya|Miroku]], [[Map of Japan (Kanazawa Bunko)|a map of Japan]], and other images designated as [[Important Cultural Properties of Japan|Important Cultural Properties]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Official Prefecture Website|url=https://www.planet.pref.kanagawa.jp/city/kanazawa.htm|website=Kanagawa Prefectural Kanazawa-Bunko Museum|publisher=Kanagawa Prefecture|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref>
Kanazawa Bunko shares its name with [[Kanazawa-Bunko Station]], which is a [[limited express]] stop station on the [[Keikyu Main Line]] of [[Keikyu]] Railways.
